{"word":"ἄμωμον","slug":"ἄμωμον","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<b><el>ἄμωμον, ου, τό</el></b> [folk-etymology (<el>ἀ-</el><a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ priv.\">priv.</a>, <el><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:μῶμος\">μῶμος</a></el>) underlies the <a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ Gk.\">Gk.</a> formation of this foreign word, suggesting <a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ perh.\">perh.</a> ‘not harmful’] an Indian spice plant, <b><i>amomum</i> <a href='B:730 18:13'>Rv 18:13</a>.</b> <center id=\"nav_bottom\"> <a id=\"left_arrow\" href=\"S:ἀμώμητος\">&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;</a> <a id=\"bottom_home\" href=\"S:#1.Table of Contents\">&emsp;&emsp;</a> <a id=\"right_arrow\" href=\"S:ἄμωμος\">&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;</a> </center> "}]}